ng, Chong, Chang, Chung, Byung, Min, Moon, Chul, Hae, Jeong, Dae, Seong, Myong.","English and Scottish: from Middle English and Older Scots <i>parc</i>, <i>parke</i>, <i>perk</i> ‘park, enclosure’ (Old French <i>parc</i>), often referring to the grounds of a manor house or a deer park where the lord hunted. The name was probably synonymous with   Parker  , denoting an officer who looked after a park for the lord of the manor.","English and Scottish: from a medieval pet form of the personal name   Peter  . Compare   Parkin  ."]}]},{"name":"Dennis","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Corrupted from the name Dionysius. According to the Annals of Ireland the old \nIrish name Donnoch or Donnchu has been sometimes Anglicised to Denis."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":24,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":33,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":60,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after t